article.description: Maurice Hargrow scored 22 points to lead Minnesota to an 84-70 win over Hawaii Monday night in the second round of the National Invitation Tournament.
article.headline: Gophers go inside to exploit smaller Rainbows
article.linkText: Gophers cruise past Hawaii into NIT quarters
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota is salvaging a little something from a disappointing season. Maurice Hargrow scored 22 points to lead the Gophers to an 84-70 win over Hawaii Monday night in the second round of the Owens Corning National Invitation Tournament. "I'm glad we're still alive,'' Hargrow said. "A lot of teams are at home now, not doing much but watching TV.'' Ben Johnson scored a season-high 18 points, Rick Rickert added 16 and Jerry Holman 14 for Minnesota, which advanced to the NIT quarterfinals against the winner of Tuesday's Temple-Rhode Island game. Tournament officials announced late Monday that Minnesota will play Thursday on the road. If they win, the Gophers go to the NIT semifinals at Madison Square Garden. "We just showed we don't want our season to end,'' Holman said. "We want to go to New York.'' After too-frequently settling for outside shots in the first half, Minnesota (18-12) attacked the basket and passed the ball inside -- something it didn't do well enough during the regular season. Even though they went with a three-guard lineup for much of the second half, the Gophers used their height advantage to outrebound the slender Rainbow Warriors 39-22 and were 21-for-27 from the foul line. Hawaii was 8-for-11. Johnson, in 28 minutes, had all but four points on drive-down-the-lane layups. "We felt this was a team we had to attack inside,'' Gophers coach Dan Monson said. Hawaii (19-12) got 20 points from Michael Kuebler and 18 from Carl English. Phil Martin Jr. added 13 points for the Warriors, who went 7-for-10 from 3-point range in the first half and led by as many as nine after halftime. English is Hawaii's leading scorer at 19.6 points per game, but Kuebler did all the damage in the first half while Hargrow -- as he did to Saint Louis star Marque Perry in the first round -- kept English in check. "That's kind of like my role on this team,'' Hargrow said. Kuebler -- who scored 21 points in Hawaii's first-round victory over UNLV -- was 5-for-7 from 3-point range in the first half. His stroke was so smooth, his makes never even hit the rim. The Warriors led by four at halftime and extended their lead to 50-41 on a 3-pointer by Kuebler with 17:18 remaining. But the Gophers got charged up, swatting shots, taking the ball strong to the basket and muscling their way to loose balls. They went on a 26-6 run, capped by consecutive 3-pointers by Hargrow from the top of the key that gave Minnesota a 67-56 lead with seven minutes to go. "I think that's home-court advantage,'' Hawaii coach Riley Wallace said. "They kind of wore us down. That was good strategy Monson had by turning it up.'' The Gophers, who beat Saint Louis on the road in the first round, are 21-8 all-time in NIT play. They won titles in 1993 and 1998, and this is their third straight appearance in the tournament. Minnesota was ousted in the second round each of the last two years at home, to Tulsa in 2001 and Richmond in 2002. "They're a good ballclub,'' Wallace said. "They might win this thing if they turn it up.'' The Warriors, making their seventh NIT appearance, made the NCAA tournament the last two seasons. Their diverse roster includes players from Guam, Nigeria, South Africa, Lithuania, Israel, Yugoslavia, Canada and the United States. "This was an absolutely fantastic bunch of kids,'' said Wallace, who loses three seniors. "They're in college for all the right reasons.'' Nkeruwem Akpan, who at 6-foot-8 and 235 pounds, was the Warriors' only real inside threat, had 12 points and fouled out with 3:33 left. The Minnesota student section -- as is custom for opposing players -- tracked his steps to the bench by chanting, "Left, right, left, right.'' The taunt is normally punctuated by a hearty "Sit down!,'' but Akpan -- grinning mischievously -- faked his final step down from the elevated Williams Arena floor three times before taking a seat and acknowledging the crowd with a point of his index finger. For its size of 4,311, the crowd was loud. "Unfortunately I have a lot of NIT experience since I've been here,'' Monson said, "but I think NIT crowds are fun. Five thousand people can be ... like 15,000 for a regular-season game, just because of the enthusiasm.''
